{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582988"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:03:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:03:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1639"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1639"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.13,0.03,0.5,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1639"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51877"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1639"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1639"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37181"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"874"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3092"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14584"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51877"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her six-month review following a gastrectomy for gastric carcinoma. She reports reduced appetite but is otherwise systemically well. She has no significant medical history apart from her recent cancer treatment. She takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A CT scan is performed for surveillance of tumour recurrence (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following can be found in this image?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liver metastasis","Enlarged retroperitoneal nodes","Skeletal metastasis","Pelvic kidney","Intraperitoneal tumour spread"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis CT scan reveals a \u003Cstrong\u003Epelvic kidney\u003C/strong\u003E, with the right kidney notable below the lumbar vertebrae (Image). This congenital abnormality is relatively common and should not raise concern - the kidney should function normally despite its atypical location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkeletal metastasis\u003C/strong\u003E is not evident in this image. While bone is a potential site for gastric cancer metastasis, there are no visible lytic or sclerotic lesions in the visible bony structures that would suggest metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurveillance for gastric cancer involves looking for recurrence at the original site, regional and distant lymph nodes, peritoneal metastasis, and metastasis to distant organs. There are \u003Cstrong\u003Eretroperitoneal nodes\u003C/strong\u003E visible in this image, however they are not enlarged, which would be expected if they contained metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver metastasis\u003C/strong\u003E is a common site for gastric cancer spread, and would typically appear as multiple hypoattenuating, well-defined lesions on CT. This is not evident in the image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no evidence of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintraperitoneal tumour spread\u003C/strong\u003E in this image. Peritoneal carcinomatosis from gastric cancer would typically appear as nodular soft tissue densities or thickening of the peritoneum, which are not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while this CT scan was performed for cancer surveillance, the most notable finding is the incidental pelvic kidney. This anatomical variant is unrelated to the patient\u0027s cancer history and does not require specific treatment. The absence of enlarged lymph nodes, metastases, or signs of recurrence is reassuring in the context of this patient\u0027s post-gastrectomy follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A pelvic kidney is a congenital abnormality that is relatively common and should not raise concern - the kidney should function normally.","CT scan is an important tool for surveillance of gastric cancer recurrence, looking for local recurrence, lymph node involvement, and distant metastases."],"references":["Aurello P, Petrucciani N, Antolino L, Giulitti D, D\u0027Angelo F, Ramacciato G. Follow-up after curative resection for gastric cancer: Is it time to tailor it?. World Journal of Gastroenterology. 2017;23(19):3379. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5442074/","Eid S, Iwanaga J, Loukas M, Oskouian RJ, Tubbs RS. Pelvic Kidney: A Review of the Literature. Cureus. 2018 Jun 9;10(6):e2775. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6084689/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37181"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1639"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17508"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17509"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17508"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/516ee5a5-9ce0-41a6-b422-1c445b251f34.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/516ee5a5-9ce0-41a6-b422-1c445b251f34.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":504,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"17509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17509"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7ee5cde5-ac0c-4389-9f49-aa34ce9c511f.j